<subSubSection id="C368650B3227983CFF481005FE30FE5E" pageId="44" pageNumber="101" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCD36803227983CFF481005FE30FE5E" blockId="44.[151,1437,258,2011]" pageId="44" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="B906EA923227983CFF481005FEA2FEC2" bold="true" box="[151,286,258,283]" pageId="44" pageNumber="101">Etymology.</emphasis>
A bezoar is an object believed to have the power of a universal antidote against any poison. The name is here used to recall the young wizard Harry Potter, the main character of a popular series of fantasy novels. The word 
<taxonomicName id="4C724D033227983CFF02104CFE95FEBA" authorityName="Sassi" authorityYear="2018" box="[221,297,331,355]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Metallactus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bezoar">
<emphasis id="B906EA923227983CFF02104CFE95FEBA" box="[221,297,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="101">bezoar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a noun in the nominative singular, standing in apposition to the generic name (art. 11.9.1.2. I.C.Z.N., 4th edition).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
